<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06025205 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06025205 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; Gaetti  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  PROFESSIONAL; BASEBALL; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Third baseman Gary Gaetti ended his 12-year career with the Minnesota Twins onThursday when he agreed on a four-year contract worth $11.4 million with theCalifornia Angels.;    Gaetti, 32, was granted new-look free agency last monthin the collusion settlement and had until Tuesday to either stay with theTwins or sign with another team.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  ANGELS SIGN GAETTI; BAINES HAS SURGERY  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Baseball NotebookMercury News Staff Writer Wayne Washington contributed to this report.  </MEMO><TEXT>     &quot;It was obviously a very tough decision,&quot; said Gaetti's agent, Jim Bronner.&quot;He felt a tremendous tie to the Twins and Minneapolis. The contract proposalswere very different. Based on the last couple of seasons, he felt it was timefor him to get a new beginning.&quot;;    Minnesota had made every effort tore-sign Gaetti, and Twins General Manager Andy MacPhail said the Minnesota'sfinal offer was restructured to meet Bronner's request.;    &quot;I'm really sadGaetti's going,&quot; MacPhail said. &quot;(Twins owner) Carl Pohlad went the extramile. Gary's agent just said it was time for a new start and we have torespect that. They wanted a philosophical change.&quot;;    The deal withCalifornia includes salaries of $2.7 million in 1991 and 1992 and $3 millionin 1993 and 1994.; SURGERY FOR BAINES: A's designated-hitter Harold Bainesunderwent arthroscopic surgery on his right knee to repair minor cartilagedamage and remove scar tissue, a team official said.;    An A's statement saidBaines, 31, is expected to make a full recovery and be available for springtraining in March.;    Baines injured the knee while taking batting practiceat his home in Maryland two weeks ago.;    The operation, Baines' third on theknee, was performed at Children's Hospital in San Francisco by teamorthopedist Rick Bost.;    Oakland acquired Baines, an 11-season veteran, in atrade Aug. 29 with the Texas Rangers. He hit .284 with 16 home runs and 65RBIs.; SIGNINGS: Pitchers Bobby Witt and Jim DeShaies signed contracts withthe Texas Rangers and Houston Astros, respectively.;    Witt signed amultiyear deal reported to be worth $6 million over three seasons, andDeShaies agreed to $2.1 million, one-year deal. DeShaies' deal also includesbonus options up to $125,000.; ETC.: Left-hander Joe Magrane avoidedarbitration and signed a one-year contract worth $1.025 million with the St.Louis Cardinals. . . . The New York Yankees signed former Giants outfielderPat Sheridan to a minor league contract and invited outfielder Dion James totheir major league camp. . . . Outfielder Max Venable has agreed to terms of aone-year contract with the California Angels. Money was not disclosed. . . .Right-hander Mark Grant and the Atlanta Braves avoided arbitration when theyagreed to a one-year contract worth $540,000, a raise of $140,000.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff and Wire Report  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910125  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  2F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  461  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday January 25, 199100025205,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>